ible sum is 4.\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [6,2,6,5,1,2]\nOutput: 9\nExplanation: The optimal pairing is (2, 1), (2, 5), (6, 6). min(2, 1) + min(2, 5) + min(6, 6) = 1 + 2 + 6 = 9.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= n <= 104\nnums.length == 2 * n\n-104 <= nums[i] <= 104\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def arrayPairSum(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def arrayPairSum(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Sort the array\n        nums.sort()\n        # Sum every second element starting from the first\n        return sum(nums[::2])\n```\n\nThis solution works by sorting the array first. When the array is sorted, the sum of every second element starting from the first will yield the maximum possible sum of the minimums of the pairs. This is because sorting ensures that the smallest elements are paired together, maximizing the contribution of the smaller element in each pair to the total sum.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}